\begin_layout Subsection
For Binary Data Matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

A natural interpretation of such binary data implies the use of the Binomial
 distribution to compute the probability of observing a given number of
 gene alterations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Thus we consider $X_1
\backslash
ldots,X_m$ random variables (number of genes present in the matrix) with
 $
\backslash
mathtt{N_1},
\backslash
ldots 
\backslash
mathtt{N_m}$ observations (replicates).
 We employ binomial distribution to model the data, assuming that every
 gene comes from the binomial distribution $X_i
\backslash
sim
\backslash
mathtt{Bin(N_i,p)}$, where parameters $N_i$ and $
\backslash
mathtt{p}$ denote the number of replicates of i and the probability of observing
 1 in a given sample, respectively.
 The precise estimate of $
\backslash
mathtt{p}$ per experiment was computed as the empirical frequency of the
 total number of alterations among $N=
\backslash
sum_{i=1}^nN_i$ samples present in the microarray.
 That is to say, if $
\backslash
mathtt{n_i}$ denotes the number of changes for a gene i, $n_i=
\backslash
sum_{k=1}^{N_i} X_{i,k}$,  we get $
\backslash
mathtt{p=
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
sum_{i=1}^mn_i}{N}}$.
 
\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

For a given experiment, the cumulative probability of observing an altered
 behavior of a gene i at least $n_i$ times in a random sample of size $N_i$
 is given by :$$
\backslash
mathtt{P(X_i
\backslash
geq n_i)=
\backslash
sum_{k=n_i}^{N_i} {N_i
\backslash
choose k} p^k(1-p)^{N_i-k}}$$
\backslash
label{eq:bin}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

